4. Specific Proposals for Research

4.1 Simplicial Lattice Formulation

Instead of hypercubic lattice, use 4-simplices. Regge calculus gives piecewise-flat approximation to manifold.

Action on Simplicial Complex  K :

S_{\text{simplicial}} = \frac{\beta}{N} \sum_{\sigma \in K^{(4)}} \left[1 - \frac{1}{N}\text{Re tr } U_{\partial\sigma}\right]

where  \sigma  is a 4-simplex,  U_{\partial\sigma}  is product of links around its boundary.

Advantages:

· Better approximation of curved spacetime
· Natural for studying quantum gravity coupling
· Improved rotational invariance

Research Goal: Prove reflection positivity and thermodynamic limit for simplicial formulation.

4.2 Exact Renormalization Group

Wetterich Equation:

\partial_t \Gamma_k = \frac{1}{2} \text{STr}\left[(\Gamma_k^{(2)} + R_k)^{-1} \partial_t R_k\right]

where  t = \log(k/\Lambda) ,  \Gamma_k  is effective average action,  R_k  is regulator.

For Yang-Mills in background field gauge:

\Gamma_k[A] = \frac{1}{4} \int d^dx \ Z_k F_{\mu\nu}^a F^{a\mu\nu} + \frac{1}{2\alpha} \int d^dx \ (D_\mu \bar{A} A_\mu)^2 + \Gamma_{\text{ghost}}

Fixed Point Analysis: Look for solutions to  \partial_t \Gamma_k = 0 . Gaussian fixed point at  g=0 , possible non-trivial fixed points for  d=4+\epsilon .

Research Goal: Solve ERG equation non-perturbatively using neural network approximations for  \Gamma_k[A] .

4.3 Conformal Bootstrap for Gauge Theories

Crossing Symmetry Equations: For four-point function of gauge-invariant operators  \mathcal{O}_i :

\sum_{\Delta, J} p_{\Delta, J} F_{\Delta, J}(u,v) = 0

where  u,v  are cross-ratios,  F_{\Delta, J}  are conformal blocks.

Numerical Bootstrap: Solve semi-definite programming problem:

\text{Maximize } \Delta_{\text{gap}} \ \text{subject to} \ \sum_{\Delta, J} p_{\Delta, J} F_{\Delta, J}^{(m,n)} \succeq 0

for derivatives  (m,n)  of crossing equation.

Research Goal: Apply bootstrap to  \text{tr}(F^2)  correlators in large-N limit to bound glueball dimensions.

4.4 Stochastic Quantization

Langevin Equation:

\frac{\partial A_\mu(x,t)}{\partial t} = -\frac{\delta S_{YM}}{\delta A_\mu(x,t)} + \eta_\mu(x,t)

with  \langle \eta_\mu^a(x,t) \eta_\nu^b(y,s) \rangle = 2\delta^{ab}\delta_{\mu\nu}\delta(x-y)\delta(t-s) .

Equilibrium Distribution:  \lim_{t\to\infty} P[A,t] \propto e^{-S_{YM}[A]} 

Complex Langevin: For real-time or sign problems, extend to complex fields.

Research Goal: Prove convergence of complex Langevin for Yang-Mills using holomorphicity of drift term.

4.5 Hamiltonian Formulation and Tensor Networks

Kogut-Susskind Hamiltonian:

H = \frac{g^2}{2} \sum_{\ell} E_\ell^a E_\ell^a + \frac{1}{2g^2} \sum_p \text{tr}(2 - U_p - U_p^\dagger)

with  [E_\ell^a, U_{\ell'}] = i\delta_{\ell\ell'} T^a U_\ell 

Tensor Network States: Ansatz for wavefunctional:

\Psi[U] = \text{tTr} \left[ \prod_{\text{sites } x} T^{[x]} \prod_{\text{links } \ell} B^{[\ell]}(U_\ell) \right]

Research Goal: Develop efficient tensor network algorithms for (2+1)D and (3+1)D Yang-Mills.

