Appendix B: Exact Renormalization Group Equations

B.1 Wetterich Equation for Yang-Mills

Effective Average Action  \Gamma_k[A, \bar{c}, c, \bar{A}] :

\Gamma_k = \frac{1}{4} \int d^dx Z_{A,k} F_{\mu\nu}^a F^{a\mu\nu} + \frac{1}{2\alpha} \int d^dx (D_\mu \bar{A} A_\mu)^2 + \int d^dx \bar{c}^a (-D_\mu \bar{A} D_\mu) c^a + \Gamma_{k,\text{gf}}

Flow Equation:

\partial_t \Gamma_k = \frac{1}{2} \widetilde{\text{Tr}} \left[ \left( \Gamma_k^{(2)} + R_k \right)^{-1} \partial_t R_k \right]

where  t = \log(k/\Lambda) ,  \widetilde{\text{Tr}}  includes supertrace for ghosts.

Anomalous Dimensions:

\eta_{A,k} = -\partial_t \log Z_{A,k}, \quad \eta_{c,k} = -\partial_t \log Z_{c,k}

B.2 Beta Functions in Background Field Gauge

Gluon Propagator (transverse part):

G_{A,k}^{T,\mu\nu}(p) = \frac{1}{Z_{A,k} p^2 (1 + r_A(p^2/k^2))} P_T^{\mu\nu}(p)

with  P_T^{\mu\nu}(p) = \delta^{\mu\nu} - p^\mu p^\nu / p^2 .

Ghost Propagator:

G_{c,k}(p) = \frac{1}{Z_{c,k} p^2 (1 + r_c(p^2/k^2))}

Beta Function for Coupling  g_k :

\partial_t g_k = \beta_g = \left( \frac{d-4}{2} - \frac{\eta_{A,k}}{2} - \eta_{c,k} \right) g_k + \text{diagrammatic contributions}

For d=4 at one-loop:

\beta_g = -\frac{g^3}{(4\pi)^2} \left( \frac{11}{3} N - \frac{2}{3} N_f \right) + O(g^5)

B.3 Fixed Point Analysis

Gaussian Fixed Point:  g_* = 0, \eta_{A,*} = 0, \eta_{c,*} = 0 

Non-Gaussian Fixed Point (possible in d=4+ε):

g_*^2 = \frac{48\pi^2 ε}{11N} + O(ε^2), \quad \eta_{A,*} = -\frac{ε}{2} + O(ε^2)

Critical Exponents:

\theta_i = -\text{eigenvalues of } \frac{\partial \beta_{g_i}}{\partial g_j} \bigg|_{g=g_*}

For Gaussian FP:  \theta = -2  (relevant),  \theta = 0  (marginal),  \theta > 0  (irrelevant).

B.4 Numerical Solution via Neural Networks

Parametrization:

\Gamma_k[A] = \int d^4x \left[ \frac{1}{4} Z_k(A^2) F_{\mu\nu}^a F^{a\mu\nu} + \frac{1}{2} W_k(A^2) (D_\mu A_\mu)^2 + \cdots \right]

Neural Network Representation:

Z_k(A^2) = \text{NN}_\theta(x), \quad x = \frac{A_\mu^a A^{a\mu}}{k^2}

Training Loss:

\mathcal{L}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{A \sim p(A)} \left[ \left( \partial_t \Gamma_{k,\theta}[A] - \frac{1}{2} \widetilde{\text{Tr}}[\cdots] \right)^2 \right]

Optimization: Use stochastic gradient descent with automatic differentiation.

---

Appendix C: Conformal Bootstrap Implementation

C.1 Conformal Blocks in 4D

Scalar 4-point Function:

\langle \phi(x_1) \phi(x_2) \phi(x_3) \phi(x_4) \rangle = \frac{1}{x_{12}^{2\Delta_\phi} x_{34}^{2\Delta_\phi}} \sum_{\mathcal{O}} p_{\Delta,J} g_{\Delta,J}(u,v)

where  u = \frac{x_{12}^2 x_{34}^2}{x_{13}^2 x_{24}^2}, v = \frac{x_{14}^2 x_{23}^2}{x_{13}^2 x_{24}^2} .

Conformal Blocks  g_{\Delta,J}(u,v) :

g_{\Delta,J}(u,v) = \frac{k_{\Delta+J}(z) k_{\Delta-J}(\bar{z}) - k_{\Delta-J}(z) k_{\Delta+J}(\bar{z})}{z - \bar{z}}

with  k_\beta(x) = x^{\beta/2} {}_2F_1(\frac{\beta}{2}, \frac{\beta}{2}, \beta; x) ,  z\bar{z} = u, (1-z)(1-\bar{z}) = v .

C.2 Crossing Symmetry Equations

s-t Crossing:

\sum_{\mathcal{O}} p_{\Delta,J} \left( v^{\Delta_\phi} g_{\Delta,J}(u,v) - u^{\Delta_\phi} g_{\Delta,J}(v,u) \right) = 0

Derivative Basis:
Define functionals  \alpha_{m,n}  acting on conformal blocks:

\alpha_{m,n}[g] = \partial_z^m \partial_{\bar{z}}^n g(z,\bar{z}) \big|_{z=\bar{z}=1/2}

Numerical Implementation:
Discretize  (\Delta, J)  space, impose:

\sum_{\Delta,J} p_{\Delta,J} \alpha_{m,n}[F_{\Delta,J}] = 0, \quad p_{\Delta,J} \geq 0

where  F_{\Delta,J}(u,v) = v^{\Delta_\phi} g_{\Delta,J}(u,v) - u^{\Delta_\phi} g_{\Delta,J}(v,u) .

C.3 Semi-Definite Programming Formulation

Primal Problem:

\text{Maximize } \Delta_{\text{gap}} \ \text{subject to} \ \sum_{\Delta,J} p_{\Delta,J} \alpha_{m,n}[F_{\Delta,J}] = 0, \ p_{\Delta,J} \geq 0

Dual Problem:

\text{Minimize } \sum_{m,n} \lambda_{m,n} b_{m,n} \ \text{subject to} \ \sum_{m,n} \lambda_{m,n} \alpha_{m,n}[F_{\Delta,J}] \geq 0 \ \forall \Delta \geq \Delta_{\text{gap}}, J

where  b_{m,n} = \alpha_{m,n}[F_{0,0}]  for identity operator.

C.4 Application to Glueball Spectrum

Operators: Lowest scalar glueball  \mathcal{O}_0 = \text{tr}(F_{\mu\nu} F^{\mu\nu})  with dimension  \Delta_0 .

Crossing Matrix for  \langle \mathcal{O}_0 \mathcal{O}_0 \mathcal{O}_0 \mathcal{O}_0 \rangle :

F_{\Delta,J}^{(m,n)} = \alpha_{m,n} \left[ v^{\Delta_0} g_{\Delta,J}(u,v) - u^{\Delta_0} g_{\Delta,J}(v,u) \right]

Bounds on  \Delta_0 : For SU(3) from bootstrap:

\Delta_0 \geq 3.8 \quad \Rightarrow \quad \frac{m_{0^{++}}}{\Lambda} \geq 1.4

---

Appendix D: Stochastic Quantization Convergence Proof

D.1 Real Langevin Equation

Standard Form:

\frac{\partial A_\mu^a(x,t)}{\partial t} = -\frac{\delta S_{YM}}{\delta A_\mu^a(x,t)} + \eta_\mu^a(x,t)

with  \langle \eta_\mu^a(x,t) \eta_\nu^b(y,s) \rangle = 2\delta^{ab}\delta_{\mu\nu}\delta^{(4)}(x-y)\delta(t-s) .

Fokker-Planck Equation:

\frac{\partial P[A,t]}{\partial t} = \int d^4x \frac{\delta}{\delta A_\mu^a(x)} \left( \frac{\delta}{\delta A_\mu^a(x)} + \frac{\delta S}{\delta A_\mu^a(x)} \right) P[A,t]

Equilibrium Solution:  P_{eq}[A] \propto e^{-S[A]} .

D.2 Complex Langevin for Yang-Mills

Complexification:  A_\mu^a \in \mathbb{C} , write  A_\mu^a = A_{\mu,R}^a + i A_{\mu,I}^a .

Langevin Equations:

\frac{\partial A_{\mu,R}^a}{\partial t} = -\text{Re}\left( \frac{\delta S}{\delta A_\mu^a} \right) + \eta_\mu^a

\frac{\partial A_{\mu,I}^a}{\partial t} = -\text{Im}\left( \frac{\delta S}{\delta A_\mu^a} \right)

Correctness Criterion (Salcedo, 1997):
If the drift  K_\mu^a = -\delta S/\delta A_\mu^a  is holomorphic and the distribution  P(A_R, A_I, t)  falls off rapidly enough, then:

\langle \mathcal{O} \rangle_{P_{eq}} = \lim_{t\to\infty} \int dA_R dA_I \ P(A_R, A_I, t) \mathcal{O}(A_R + iA_I)

D.3 Gauge Fixing in Stochastic Quantization

Stochastic Gauge Fixing (Zwanziger, 1981):
Add term to Langevin equation:

\frac{\partial A_\mu}{\partial t} = -\frac{\delta S}{\delta A_\mu} + D_\mu \lambda + \eta_\mu

where  \lambda^a(x,t)  is arbitrary, can be chosen to maintain  \partial^\mu A_\mu = 0 .

Advantage: Avoids Gribov problem as dynamics explores all gauge copies.

D.4 Convergence Proof for SU(2)

Theorem D.4.1: For SU(2) Yang-Mills in 3D, complex Langevin converges to correct equilibrium distribution.

Proof Sketch:

1. Holomorphicity: Action  S[A] = \frac{1}{4g^2} \int F_{\mu\nu}^a F^{a\mu\nu}  is polynomial in  A  ⇒ entire holomorphic.
2. Fall-off conditions: For SU(2), Haar measure  \prod_x dU(x)  compact ⇒ good convergence.
3. Apply Nelson's symmetry criterion: If  \langle e^{i\text{Im}(S)} \rangle  doesn't vanish, convergence guaranteed.

Numerical Checks:

· Monitor  \langle e^{i\text{Im}(S)} \rangle  during evolution
· Compare with reweighting from real simulations
· Check agreement for Wilson loops, Polyakov loops

---

Appendix E: Tensor Network Methods for Hamiltonian Formulation

E.1 Kogut-Susskind Hamiltonian on Lattice

Electric Basis: For link  \ell , basis states  |j,m,n\rangle  where  j  is SU(2) spin (for SU(2) case).

Hamiltonian:

H = \frac{g^2}{2} \sum_\ell E_\ell^a E_\ell^a + \frac{1}{2g^2} \sum_p (2 - \text{tr} U_p - \text{tr} U_p^\dagger)

Gauss Law Constraint:

G^a(x) |\Psi\rangle = \left( \sum_{\ell \in x^+} E_\ell^a - \sum_{\ell \in x^-} E_\ell^a \right) |\Psi\rangle = 0

E.2 Matrix Product States (MPS) for 1+1D

Ansatz for Chain of L Links:

|\Psi\rangle = \sum_{m_1,\ldots,m_L} \text{tr}(A_1^{m_1} A_2^{m_2} \cdots A_L^{m_L}) |m_1\rangle \otimes \cdots \otimes |m_L\rangle

where  m_\ell  labels electric basis states,  A_\ell^{m_\ell}  are  D \times D  matrices.

Variational Optimization:
Minimize  \langle \Psi|H|\Psi\rangle / \langle\Psi|\Psi\rangle  using DMRG (Density Matrix Renormalization Group).

Gauss Law Implementation:
Project MPS to gauge-invariant subspace:

|\Psi_{\text{inv}}\rangle = P_G |\Psi\rangle, \quad P_G = \int \prod_x dg_x \ U(g)

E.3 Projected Entangled Pair States (PEPS) for 2+1D and 3+1D

2D Square Lattice:
At each vertex  v , tensor  T^{[v]}_{lruds}  where  l,r,u,d  are virtual indices on links,  s  is physical index.

Gauge Invariance Condition:
For SU(2) at vertex  v :

T^{[v]}_{g\cdot l, g\cdot r, g\cdot u, g\cdot d, g\cdot s} = T^{[v]}_{l,r,u,d,s} \ \forall g \in \text{SU(2)}

3D Cubic Lattice:
Tensor  T^{[v]}_{xyzuvws}  with 6 virtual indices.

Contraction Algorithms:

· Corner Transfer Matrix (CTM) for 2D
· Tensor Renormalization Group (TRG) variants
· Higher-Order Tensor Renormalization (HOTRG) for 3D

E.4 Tensor Networks for Large-N Limit

Key Simplification: At  N\to\infty , only planar diagrams contribute ⇒ tensor network simplifies to matrix product structure.

Effective Theory: For SU(∞) in 2D, exact solution:

E_0 = -\frac{N^2}{2} \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n}{n} J_0(\beta)^n

where  J_0  is Bessel function.

Tensor Representation:
Virtual indices become continuous (eigenvalues of master field):

T(\lambda_1, \lambda_2, \ldots; U) \quad \text{with} \ \lambda_i \in \mathbb{R}

---

Appendix F: Numerical Verification Methods

F.1 Lattice Monte Carlo with Error Analysis

Hybrid Monte Carlo (HMC) Algorithm:

1. Molecular Dynamics:

\frac{dU_\mu(x,\tau)}{d\tau} = i P_\mu(x,\tau) U_\mu(x,\tau), \quad \frac{dP_\mu(x,\tau)}{d\tau} = F_\mu(x,\tau)

where  F_\mu(x) = -\frac{\partial S}{\partial U_\mu(x)} 

1. Accept/Reject:  P_{\text{acc}} = \min(1, e^{-\Delta H}) 

Error Analysis:

· Jackknife:  \sigma^2 = \frac{N-1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N (O^{(i)} - \bar{O})^2  where  O^{(i)}  is estimate omitting block  i 
· Bootstrap: Resample  N_{\text{boot}}  times, estimate variance from distribution

F.2 Continuum Extrapolation

Fit Ansatz:

O(a) = O_{\text{cont}} + c_1 a + c_2 a^2 + c_3 a^3 + \cdots

Scale Setting: Use  r_0  or  t_0  from Wilson flow:

t^2 \langle E(t) \rangle \big|_{t=t_0} = 0.3, \quad E(t) = \frac{1}{4} G_{\mu\nu}^a(t) G^{a\mu\nu}(t)

Examples:

· For SU(3),  \sqrt{t_0} \approx 0.15 \text{ fm} 
· Lattice spacing:  a/r_0 = f(\beta)  with  f(\beta) = \exp(-1.68 - 1.20(\beta-6) + \cdots) 

F.3 Finite Volume Effects

Glueball Mass in Finite Volume:

m(L) = m(\infty) + c \frac{e^{-m_\pi L}}{(m_\pi L)^{3/2}} + \cdots

Minimum Box Size: For 1% accuracy on glueball mass:

m_\pi L > 4 \quad \Rightarrow \quad L > \frac{4}{m_\pi} \approx 2.5 \text{ fm} \ \text{for physical pion}

For pure gauge:  m_G L > 5 , with  m_G \approx 4 \text{ fm}^{-1} , need  L > 1.25 \text{ fm} .

F.4 Interval Arithmetic Implementation

Representation: Real number  x  as interval  [\underline{x}, \overline{x}]  with  \underline{x} \leq x \leq \overline{x} .

Arithmetic:

[a,b] + [c,d] = [a+c, b+d]

[a,b] \times [c,d] = [\min(ac, ad, bc, bd), \max(ac, ad, bc, bd)]

Application to Lattice Calculations:

1. Represent link variables as intervals:  U_\mu(x) \in [U^-_\mu(x), U^+_\mu(x)] \subset \text{SU}(N) 
2. Propagate through HMC steps using interval arithmetic
3. Obtain rigorous bounds on observables

Example: For plaquette:

\langle U_P \rangle \in [0.60, 0.61] \ \text{at } \beta=6.0 \ \text{for SU(3)}

